{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ca82ab2f-8779-47b1-9a67-560dea715832","content":"Here's the evaluation performance analysis for `EvalHeavy.csproj`:\n\n## Issues Found\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading file contents during evaluation is expensive — it blocks the evaluation thread with synchronous I/O. This runs on **every** evaluation (IDE design-time builds, restores, etc.).\n\n**Fix:** Read the file in a target at execution time instead, or use an item if you only need the path.\n\n### 2. Overly Broad Glob (Medium Impact)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThis walks the entire directory tree. If the project sits in a large repo or has `node_modules`/`.git`/artifacts nearby, evaluation stalls while enumerating files. Add more exclusions via `DefaultItemExcludes` or narrow the glob scope.\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (Low Impact here, scales poorly)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree-deep is manageable, but this pattern indicates potential for growth. At >20 levels, evaluation time increases noticeably. Keep import chains shallow and flat where possible.\n\n---\n\n**Priority:** Fix #1 (file read) first — it's the most reliably expensive. Then scope down the glob in #2.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"06b2bf18-027f-4ce5-b019-9cf23ed39511","outputTokens":365,"requestId":"1902:1C0D12:151E0A6:17AD97C:6A067544"},"id":"c86f0afa-2020-460c-b6f8-69a4254f4805","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:22:23.618Z","parentId":"6e161d58-3f60-4b3f-a64f-50b603219092"}
